http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Alabama Course of Study: Arts Education Dance

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Achieving Excellence Through Arts Literacy is the goal of Alabama's K-12 arts education program.  Encompassing the disciplines of dance, music, theatre, and visual arts, the arts education program provides opportunities for students to explore the interrelationship of these disciplines as well as the specific nature of each arts area.  To emphasize the importance of the arts for Alabama students, the Alabama Course of Study:  Arts Education provides rigorous standards for all students in Grades K-12.  This document incorporates national standards and provides for the development of skills in each discipline and an appreciation of the importance the arts play in all societies and cultures.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understand
Perform partnered sequences with technical proficiency.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: demonstrating leading and following in a cha-cha or supporting and balancing in pas de deux, illustrating equal responsibility for support in contact improvisation

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Compare correct body alignment in various dance techniques.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: hips leading in fall and recovery compared to hips remaining under shoulders for tombé pas de bourré

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the impact of major personalities and historical factors on dance in the twentieth and twenty-first centuries.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: explaining the importance of collaborations between Merce Cunningham, John Cage, and Robert Rauschenberg; interpreting the impact of the events of September 11, 2001, on current artistic works

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain healthy ways to acquire optimum weight as a dancer.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: eating a balanced diet

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describing ways dancers avoid eating disorders
Explaining appropriate methods for stretching and conditioning muscles
Create a dance that communicates a topic from another content area.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: creating a dance that reflects deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) replication

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Level IV Dance
Produce
Create dance using a variety of dance technologies.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: composing movement using computer software, digital projectors and cameras, and interactive multimedia

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choreograph a dance utilizing a variety of compositional methods.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: using choreography by chance; employing motif and development, including retrograde, fragmentation, inversion, and diminution; using theme and variation

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply variations in time, space, and energy to choreography and performance.
Demonstrate the ability to increase technical proficiency, including strength, stamina, and consistency.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: dancing the "Garland Dance" from Marius Petipa's The Sleeping Beauty,  dancing the role of Laurie in the "Dream Ballet" from the musical Oklahoma!

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performing specialized dance techniques

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: contact improvisation, Russian traditional dance, pas de deux

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Create a dance for production, including costumes, lighting, sound, and makeup.
Organizing complete rehearsal and production schedules
Respond
Explain how movement elements and production choices affect the impact of choreography.
Comparing sound scores and music choices
Evaluating master works to determine content, context, and compositional elements

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: analyzing Jerome Robbins' The Cage for elements of feminism, analyzing Frederick Ashton's Winter Dreams for parallels to Romanticism

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate choreographic influence on dance works.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: George Balanchine's influence on twentieth-century classical dance, Merce Cunningham's influence on modern dance choreography

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understand
Create partnered dance sequences with fluidity and control.
Analyze the development of dance to determine its relationship to political, social, artistic, and scientific developments.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: analyzing Anna Sokolow's Dreams and the impact of the Holocaust, analyzing social injustice in Donald McKayle's Rainbow 'Round My Shoulder

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Create a dance project utilizing abstract concepts that bridge content areas.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examples: translating newspaper text into movement, creating movement based on thoughts or analogies

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Create an individual dance-wellness plan.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: establishing a calendar that includes exercise and eating plans

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply kinesiological concepts to dance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: identifying most efficient muscle or muscle groups to perform specific actions

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate performance skills to determine proper alignment, projection, stage presence, memory, interpretation, focus, musicality, and execution.
